Good morning everyone!
Yesterday evening a friend saw a post on a local sell and seek page about a rabbit in some woodlands. They had been unable to catch it, and was wondering if anyone had lost a pet rabbit.

My friends and I decided to go and try and catch the rabbit, as it obviously wouldn't be safe there (the woods is on a 60mph country road plus foxes are rife in the area).
Over 2 hours later, running up and down hills, throwing blankets, lots of bramble scratches and scrapes from throwing myself on the floor, we managed to catch not 1, but 2 rabbits!
Both obviously pet rabbits, as once we had caught them they were very friendly.

We aren't sure how long they have been out there, but they look to have been looked after, and luckily none of them have any injuries.

We have obviously posted on all the local social media pages, and contacted the local vet, in the hope if someone's rabbits have got out, they can be reunited.

I'll be taking them both to the vets today to be scanned for a microchip and have a health check!

We have named them Acorn (Agouti) and Garlic (Dutch looking) - as the woodlands was covered in a carpet of garlic (which incidentally gets very slippery after running around on it!).

Here are some pictures! This morning I feel like I've run a marathon!
The last picture has the woodlands we were in, outlined in pink, so you can see not many houses are around!

Wild rabbit rillette - bubbling away after coming out of the pressure cooker. The bunnies were in really good condition, the meat tender and very mild in taste. They spent 24 hours with salt, pepper, garlic, thyme and marjoram before being cooked in pork fat for 3.5 hours before being potted and going into the pressure cooker. The great thing about rabbit is that the bones after meat comes off makes a fantastic bunny broth. Thanks to the folk @motutara_farm_produce for access to the bunny land.

üêæ FREE ACTIVITY PAGE üêæ 

Introducing the newest Animals Everywhere printable activity page! Have fun while learning about animals from around the world.  Perfect for children k-6 who love animals. 

Just click the link in my bio, download and print on a 8.5 x 11 sheet of paper.

April has another well known animal incorporated holiday. Whether you celebrate it or not almost everyone has heard of the Easter bunny. There is a lot of different theories as to what the bunny has to do with the holiday, many involve the rabbit being a symbol of fertility and new life. That is true about rabbits, the Eastern Cottontail rabbit can have 1-7 litters a year each containing 1-12 babies! That‚Äôs a lot of bunnies. 

Rabbits need to reproduce a lot because they are prey animals. A lot of predators eat rabbits, so the bigger the population the more likely they are to survive and keep the species going. Eastern Cottontail rabbits are the most common species in North America. They mainly live around the east coast but have been recorded as far west as Arizona. They can also live in a wide variety of ecosystems but like open grassy areas with plenty of places to hide best.

A day in the random life: caring for an injured wild bun. üêá

By the time our native rabbits are this size, they are weaned and mobile if not fully independent. They are best left to their own if found, but this little one has a gash that needs some healing before running free. ü§ï

Respect wild animals and their space. They usually don‚Äôt need help. Consult experts like wildlife rehabbers (which I am not) on care and be very careful intervening. Little cottontail is pooping (key to bun survival) and recouping well. Hopefully will be released in the next couple of days! üèÉ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è

PS. Also having to be particularly careful keeping completely separate and sanitizing frequently to protect my domestic bun from any wild contaminants. üò∑

Red foxes are typically born in late March or early April, often in dens located on sandy hillsides. For the first ten days, the mother is restricted to the den and the male fox will bring her food. After that period, both parents will leave the young unattended for several hours at a time while hunting. If you find one alone, leave it be and leave the area. An adult will likely be back soon with a snack!

If you find truly orphaned or injured wildlife, always contact a licensed wildlife rehabilitator for assistance (list available on our website). Wildlife rehabbers are trained on the extensive care requirements of many of Indiana's native wildlife species and are able to help wildlife recover without losing their natural fear of people.
